<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<worksheet>
  <title>Section 2.6 - The geometry of matrix transformations</title>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>Matrix transformation perform geometric operations. Go to <url href="https://gvsu.edu/s/0Jf" visual="gvsu.edu/s/0Jf">this website</url> to
study the effect that various matrix transformations have on the plane. On the left
is the plane before the transformation; on the right is the plane after the transformation.</p>
      <p>Describe the geometric effect of the matrix transformations defined by</p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p><m>A = \left[\begin{array}{cc}2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1\end{array}\right]</m></p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Scales by 2 in the <m>x</m>-direction.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p><m>A = \left[\begin{array}{cc}2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 2\end{array}\right]</m></p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Scales by 2 in both the <m>x</m>-direction and <m>y</m>-direction.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p><m>A = \left[\begin{array}{cc}0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0\end{array}\right]</m></p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Rotates by <m>90^o</m> counterclockwise.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p><m>A = \left[\begin{array}{cc}1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1\end{array}\right]</m></p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Skews to the right.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p><m>A = \left[\begin{array}{cc}-1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1\end{array}\right]</m></p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Flips over the <m>y</m>-axis.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p><m>A = \left[\begin{array}{cc}1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0\end{array}\right]</m></p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Projects (condenses) on to the <m>x</m>-axis.  Note: columns are not linearly independent.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p><m>A = \left[\begin{array}{cc}1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1\end{array}\right]</m></p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Nothing! This is the identity matrix!
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p><m>A = \left[\begin{array}{cc}1 \amp -1 \\ -2 \amp 2\end{array}\right]</m></p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Projects onto a line and stretches. Note: columns are not linearly independent.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Transformations that scale.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Find the matrix <m>A</m> that defines the transformation <m>T</m> that scales all vectors horizontally by <m>3</m> and vertically by <m>5</m>. You can go to <url href="https://gvsu.edu/s/0Jf" visual="gvsu.edu/s/0Jf">this website</url> to check your work (with smaller numbers)!</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let's think about the action we want with respect to our vectors <m>\evec_1</m> and <m>\evec_2</m>.
          First, we want to take <m>\evec_1 = \twovec{1}{0}</m> and scale this horizontally by 3 (note: the vertical
          component is zero here).  This means if we input <m>\twovec{1}{0}</m>,
          the output should be <m>\twovec{3}{0}</m> to scale by 3 horizontally (1st coordinate).
        </p>
        <p>
          Then, for <m>\evec_2 = \twovec{0}{1}</m> and scale this verically by 5 (note: the horizontal
          component is zero here).  This means if we input <m>\twovec{0}{1}</m>,
          the output should be <m>\twovec{0}{5}</m> to scale by 5 vertically (2nd coordinate).
        </p>
        <p>
          Therefore, we have <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix} </m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>In general, what is the matrix that that will define the transformation that scales all vectors horizontally by <m>a</m> and vertically by <m>b</m>?</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            \begin{bmatrix} a \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp b \end{bmatrix}
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        What matrix produces a <m>180^o</m> rotation? (Find <m>T(\evec_1)</m> and <m>T(\evec_2)</m>
        to find the matrix - you can check it using the applet.)
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
          Again, we look at the action of the transformation on our vectors <m>\evec_1</m> and <m>\evec_2</m>. So,
          <md>
            T(\evec_1) = T\left(\twovec{1}{0}\right) = \twovec{-1}{0} \\
            T(\evec_2) = T\left(\twovec{0}{1}\right) = \twovec{0}{-1} \\
          </md>
          Therefore, the matrix that produces this transformation is
          <md>
            \begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}.
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        What matrix produces a reflection over the line <m>y = -x</m>? (Find <m>T(\evec_1)</m> and <m>T(\evec_2)</m>
        to find the matrix - you can check it using the applet.)
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
          Again, we look at the action of the transformation on our vectors <m>\evec_1</m> and <m>\evec_2</m>. So,
          <md>
            T(\evec_1) = T\left(\twovec{1}{0}\right) = \twovec{0}{-1} \\
            T(\evec_2) = T\left(\twovec{0}{1}\right) = \twovec{-1}{0} \\
          </md>
          Therefore, the matrix that produces this transformation is
          <md>
            \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp -1 \\ -1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}.
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>All of the transformations in this question have the form <m>T: \real^2 \to \real^2</m>.</p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Find the matrix of the transformation that has no effect on vectors; that is, <m>T(\xvec) = \xvec</m>. We call this matrix the identity and denote it by <m>I</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We saw in Problem 1(g) that the identity matrix has no transformational effect on vectors.
          Additionally, note that <m>I\xvec = \xvec</m>.  Therefore, <m>T(\xvec) = \xvec = I\xvec</m>,
          such that the corresponding matrix for this transformation is <m>{I = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}.}</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Find the matrix <m>B</m> of the transformation that reflects vectors in <m>\real^2</m>
 over the line <m>y=x</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Again, we look at the action of the transformation on our vectors <m>\evec_1</m> and <m>\evec_2</m>. So,
          <md>
            T(\evec_1) = T\left(\twovec{1}{0}\right) = \twovec{0}{1} \\
            T(\evec_2) = T\left(\twovec{0}{1}\right) = \twovec{1}{0} \\
          </md>
          Therefore, the matrix that produces this transformation is
          <md>
          B = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}.
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What is the result of composing the reflection you found in the previous part with itself; that is, what is the effect of reflecting in the line <m>y=x</m>  and then reflecting in this line again. Provide a geometric explanation for your result as well as an algebraic one obtained by multiplying matrices.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          This corresponds to 
          <md>
            B^2 = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} = \left[\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\twovec{0}{1} \,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,  \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\twovec{1}{0}\right] \\
            = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} = I.
          </md>
          Thus, reflecting twice returns to the original vector.  This makes geometric sense!
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>More composing transformations.</p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Find the matrix <m>C</m> that rotates vectors counterclockwise in the plane by <m>90^\circ</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We look at the action of the transformation on our vectors <m>\evec_1</m> and <m>\evec_2</m>. So,
          <md>
            T(\evec_1) = T\left(\twovec{1}{0}\right) = \twovec{0}{1} \\
            T(\evec_2) = T\left(\twovec{0}{1}\right) = \twovec{-1}{0} \\
          </md>
          Therefore, the matrix that produces this transformation is
          <md>
          C = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}.
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Find the matrix that results from composing a <m>90^\circ</m> rotation with itself. Explain the geometric meaning of this operation. Find the matrix that results from composing a 
<m>90^\circ</m> rotation with itself four times; that is, if <m>T</m> is the matrix transformation that rotates vectors by <m>90^\circ</m> find the matrix for <m>T\circ T \circ T \circ T</m>. Explain why your result makes sense geometrically.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Compare the result of rotating by <m>90^\circ</m>  and then reflecting over the line  <m>y=x</m>
 to the result of first reflecting over <m>y=x</m> and then rotating <m>90^\circ</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Do matrix transformations ``commute"? That is, if <m>S</m> and <m>T</m> are two transformations, is <m>S\circ T = T\circ S</m>?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>Explain why the matrix that rotates vectors counterclockwise by an angle <m>\theta</m> is 
<md>\begin{bmatrix}
\cos\theta \amp-\sin\theta\\
\sin\theta \amp\cos\theta
\end{bmatrix}.</md></p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <outcomes>
    <ul>
      <li><p>What is the matrix for a transformation that scales horizontally by a factor of <m>a</m> and vertically by a factor of <m>b</m>?</p></li>
      <li><p>What is the matrix for a transformation that rotates counterclockwise by an angle <m>\theta</m>?</p></li>
      <li><p>How can you find the matrix associated with the composition of two matrix transformations?</p></li>
    </ul>
  </outcomes>

</worksheet>
